<div class="body"><p> In short, by slapping Boris down, Mr Cameron has bigged him up - he certainly has as far the media narrative is concerned. Journalists can’t be blamed for revelling in the Dave v Boris bust-up. It’s a damn sight more interesting than wading through the weeds of the European Union’s rules and regs. Even the BBC - who we should be able to rely on to do the boring but important detail of political history – spontaneously combusted at news of Boris’s Brexit intentions. </p><p> Boris can’t be ignored by the PM, of course. He is popular and can generate more coverage than any politician other than, irritatingly, the man he seeks to oust. But No10 have mistaken popularity for persuasiveness. And the ability to persuade is what will, in the end, be tested on June 23. </p><p>
</p><div class="videoPlayer">
