</aside><script src="http://cf.eip.telegraph.co.uk/particle-embed/js/particle.js"></script><p></p><p> In contrast to Boris, the Prime Minister is the only man capable of making a detailed, pragmatic case for his team, although he has, so far, also failed to provide the detail required. But there’s time, and even those who dislike Mr Cameron grudgingly admire his uncanny ability to convince, especially when his back is against the wall. </p><p> The Prime Minister, though, should not engage in hand-to-hand combat with Boris; he should delegate the man-marking. In fact, Boris should be woman-marked by Theresa May. He has always struggled to take on female opponents and my money would be on the Home Secretary every time. </p><p> <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/11131190/Boris-Johnson-vs-Theresa-May-who-would-make-better-Conservative-Party-leader.html">As a front runner for the Tory leadership herself</a>, she would provide a powerful contrast to Boris on the vital questions of loyalty and motive. And it’s win-win: if she can help in the blowing up of Boris, it’ll be one less rival for her to deal with down the road. </p><p> David Cameron is paid by us to worry about Vladimir Putin. He should leave it to others to fret about an ambitious, outgoing Mayor - at least until the day after the referendum. </p><p> <strong><i>Andy Coulson is former No 10 Comms Director</i></strong> </p><p> <iframe frameborder="0" height="350" id="tweetframe" scrolling="no" src="http://renderer.qmerce.com/interaction/56ca288be5be274a1fcdb1a6" width="100%"></iframe> </p></div>

